column65: The study enrolled healthy participants aged 9-49 years. The total number of participants enrolled was 1308, with 1299 receiving the study vaccine. This included 641 participants (49%) in the 9-17 years age group and 658 participants (51%) in the 18-49 years age group. The mean age for the 9-17 years group was 13.0 years (SD 2.5), and for the 18-49 years group, it was 34.3 years (SD 9.2). Overall, 54% of participants were female and 46% were male. Most participants (77%) were White, followed by Black or African American (19%), and 11% identified as Hispanic or Latino.
column2139: The study was a phase 3, non-randomised, immunobridging, open-label, uncontrolled, multicenter study conducted in 36 centers in the USA and Europe (Poland, Czech Republic, and Spain) during the 2022-23 northern hemisphere influenza season. It aimed to demonstrate non-inferior immune responses and safety of a quadrivalent recombinant influenza vaccine (RIV4) in participants aged 9-17 years compared with adults aged 18-49 years. The primary outcomes, assessed at day 29, were non-inferiority of immune response by HAI titre ratios and differences in seroconversion rates. The study concluded RIV4 induced non-inferior immune responses and showed a comparable safety profile in the 9-17 years age group versus the 18-49 years age group, with no safety concerns reported. The findings support a potential license extension for RIV to the pediatric population aged 9 years and older.

column2139: Across 727 vaccinations in the vaccine series, the bivalent (Pfizer) booster induced fewer adverse reactions than earlier doses. Fever ≥ 38.0 ◦C was significantly less frequent in the bivalent booster (12.3 %) compared to the primary series and monovalent booster (22.0 %, 26.2 %, p < 0.001). Reaction severity was also reduced in the bivalent booster. In the analysis of 70 participants with complete data for all doses, post-vaccination fever ≥38.0 ◦C exhibited the highest relative risk (RR) among all solicited reactions throughout the vaccine series (RR:5.24 [95 % CI: 2.40-11.42] for monovalent and 6.24 [95 % CI: 2.14-18.15] for bivalent). The frequency of fever ≥ 38.0 ◦ C after all doses was 8.6 % (6/70), with no fever ≥ 39.0 ◦C across all vaccinations. A high-grade post-vaccination fever was correlated with higher IgG titers, with multivariate analyses confirming this correlation as independent for each dose and unaffected by previous post-vaccination fever

column2139: mRNA vaccine is included as disaggregated. Influenza vaccines is all types from the 60s to 2023. Not sure if this should be excluded based on study type but leaving for second reviewer opinion. - Derek    In case it's useful, here's the aggregate flu vaccine data:   Influenza vaccines showed the highest signal for association with narcolepsy out of all vaccines studied. Overall Risk Signal: The reported odds ratio for all influenza vaccines combined was 156.53 (95% CI, 147.62-165.97). Subgroup Analysis: The signal was particularly high for the Pandemrix vaccine (ROR 852.31) but was also significant for non-Pandemrix influenza vaccines (ROR 122.67).  Highest-Risk Population: For influenza vaccines, the strongest signal was observed in individuals aged 12 to 17 years. Time to Onset: The mean time to onset following influenza vaccination was 146 days.  Influenza vaccines showed the strongest disproportionality for narcolepsy: ROR 156.53 (95% CI 147.62-165.97) overall and 112.19 (105.32-119.51) in health-professional-only reports.

column80: "Statistical criteria were prespecified to demonstrate the noninferiority of V116 immunogenicity when administered concomitantly with QIV compared to sequential administration. V116 administered concomitantly with QIV met the noninferiority criterion to V116 administered sequentially with QIV for 20 of 21 serotypes contained in V116, and QIV administered concomitantly with V116 met the noninferiority criterion to QIV administered sequentially with V116 for 3 of 4 strains contained in QIV. In the 2 endpoints where noninferiority cutoffs were missed, they were missed by a narrow margin. For V116, serotype 23B missed the noninferiority cutoff for OPA but the IgG GMC following vaccination in the concomitant group (4.24 μg/ml) supports that an immune response to serotype 23B was induced. In addition, supporting data evaluating the proportion of participants with a ≥4-fold rise in OPA GMTs from pre- to postvaccination with V116, and the proportion of participants with ≥1:40 HAI titers after QIV, demonstrated robust immune responses were induced to all components of both vaccines."
